          "body": "When news of Lot's capture reaches Abram, the text records no deliberation. He 'led out his trained men, born in his house, three hundred and eighteen, and went in pursuit.' The word for 'trained men' (*chanikh*) appears only here in the Old Testament; it denotes men specifically prepared for combat, members of Abram's extended household rather than hired mercenaries. The number 318 is specific enough to suggest historical record rather than literary convention. Abram's military strategy is equally concrete: he divides his forces for a night attack, routing the coalition as far as Hobah, north of Damascus. The same verb (*nakhah*, 'struck down') used of Chedorlaomer's earlier victories is now applied to Abram — Moses is signaling intentional parallelism. What the great king had done sweeping through Transjordan, Abram accomplishes with a fraction of the force. The narrator will supply the theological explanation in Melchizedek's blessing: 'God Most High has delivered your enemies into your hand' (14:20). The strategy was Abram's; the victory was God's."
