        "body": "Abram's response to the news of Lot's capture reveals three things about his character that the narrative has not yet shown directly. First, he acts immediately and without hesitation — no deliberation, no consultation, no weighing of odds. Covenant loyalty to kin is non-negotiable. Second, he is a man of prepared capacity — the 318 trained men born in his household are not improvised; they are maintained, suggesting that Abram has been a person of substantial household authority all along, even when the narrative had focused on his faith and wandering. Third, he is strategically intelligent — the night attack with divided forces is not the tactic of a desperate man; it is the tactic of someone who assesses his enemy and exploits vulnerability.\n\nThe narrative's reticence about divine intervention during the battle itself is striking. Unlike later holy-war accounts (Joshua 10:10-11; Judges 7), there is no explicit angelic intervention, no hailstones, no divine voice during the fight. The miracle is embedded in the outcome: 318 men rout a coalition that had swept the entire Transjordanian ridge. Melchizedek will supply the theological explanation after the fact (v.20): 'God Most High has delivered your enemies into your hand.' The faith required here is precisely the faith to act without visible supernatural support, trusting that the God of the covenant is working through ordinary means.\n\nVerse 16 is metrically careful: 'He brought back all the goods, and also brought back his relative Lot with his possessions, and also the women, and the people.' The repetition of 'brought back' (*shuv*, used twice) emphasizes complete recovery. Nothing is missing. The rescue is total — goods, people, women, all named. This sets up the king of Sodom's offer in verse 21 with precise irony: Abram has already given back everything; the king now offers Abram what Abram just returned.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chanikh* (trained men, v.14) — a hapax legomenon in the OT, from a root meaning to initiate or train. *Radaph* (pursue, vv.14-15) — the same word used for pursuing an enemy to total defeat; Abram does not stop at recovery but completes the rout. *Chalaq* (divide, v.15) — to divide forces; a standard ancient military tactic for surrounding a fleeing enemy."
