        "body": "Melchizedek's appearance is exegetically sovereign — the chapter cannot be understood without him, and he cannot be understood without the canonical trajectory he initiates. He appears between the battle and the temptation (the king of Sodom's offer), positioned as the theological interpreter of the victory before the ethical test of the aftermath. His identity is loaded: *Malkitsedeq* means 'my king is righteousness'; *Salem* means peace or wholeness (the root of *shalom*); his office combines kingship and priesthood, which in the ancient Near East were typically separated. He is, in the chapter's own terms, simultaneously king of righteousness and king of peace — titles the author of Hebrews will apply directly to Christ (Hebrews 7:2).\n\nThe bread and wine he brings (v.18) is a provision for Abram's returning troops, but its canonical resonance is inescapable. The combination of bread and wine as elements of priestly provision will recur at the Passover, at the wilderness manna, and ultimately at the Last Supper. Jesus identifies His body and blood with bread and wine (Matthew 26:26-28) in a context thick with priestly overtones. The typological trajectory from Melchizedek's provision to the Eucharistic table is one of the most carefully drawn types in Scripture — not an allegory imposed from outside but a pattern embedded in the text and explicitly identified by Hebrews 7.\n\nHis blessing in verses 19-20 is doubly directed: toward Abram ('Blessed be Abram of God Most High') and toward God ('And blessed be God Most High, who has delivered your enemies'). The double movement is important. Melchizedek does not merely speak well of Abram; he attributes Abram's victory to God and then praises God for it. He is a mediator of blessing in both directions — downward to the patriarch, upward to the Sovereign. This is precisely the priestly function: to stand between God and humanity, carrying the human before God and the divine down to the human. Abram's tithe (v.20b) is not a tax; it is a worshipful response to Melchizedek's priestly mediation.\n\nThe New Testament exposition of this encounter is the most extensive in Scripture for any Genesis passage outside Genesis 1-3. Hebrews 5:6, 10; 6:20; 7:1-28 construct a typological argument in which Melchizedek's lack of recorded genealogy represents an eternal priesthood (Hebrews 7:3), the tithe proves Melchizedek's superiority to Levi (Hebrews 7:9-10), and Psalm 110:4 ('You are a priest forever according to the order of Melchizedek') is applied to the risen Christ's permanent, non-transferable priestly office. What Genesis 14 plants as a narrative episode, the canon waters into full-blown Christology.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *El Elyon* — God Most High — first occurrence of *Elyon* as a divine title in Scripture, here and vv.19-20, 22. *Qanah* (Possessor/Creator, vv.19, 22) — can mean 'to acquire' or 'to create'; most Hebrew scholars take it as 'Creator' in this context (cf. Deuteronomy 32:6; Psalm 139:13). *Maaser* (tithe, v.20) — tenth; first biblical tithe, predating the Mosaic law by roughly four centuries."
