        "body": "The chapter's moral and theological climax is not the battle but the refusal. Having worshipped God Most High through Melchizedek and the tithe, Abram faces the king of Sodom's offer: keep the goods; give me the people. The offer is commercially fair — the goods are spoils of war that Abram recovered by his own effort. But Abram refuses with an oath already sworn before the battle ('I have raised my hand' — the perfect tense implies the oath preceded the offer, perhaps in connection with the tithe and blessing of vv.18-20).\n\nThe reasoning Abram gives is theologically precise: 'for fear you would say, I have made Abram rich.' Abram is not refusing because the goods are tainted (though Sodom's wickedness is established). He is refusing because accepting them would introduce a competing narrative about the source of his wealth. If Sodom's king can plausibly claim credit for Abram's prosperity, then the testimony of Genesis 12:2 — 'I will bless you' — is diluted. God's blessing must remain unambiguous. D. A. Carson observes that this pattern — refusing legitimate good to protect the integrity of a greater witness — appears repeatedly in Paul (1 Corinthians 9:12-18: refusing financial support to prevent the gospel from being associated with mercenary motives). The principle is apostolic before it is apostolic.\n\nAbram's exception for his allies (v.24) is equally revealing. 'Let them take their share' — Aner, Eshcol, and Mamre are not bound by Abram's oath to God Most High. They had not yet received Melchizedek's blessing or participated in Abram's tithe. Abram's integrity does not require others to match it; it insists on justice for those who fought alongside him while refusing, for himself, what would compromise his testimony. Jonathan Edwards noted in *The Nature of True Virtue* that genuine love for God produces not abstract renunciation but careful practical wisdom about when to take and when to refuse.\n\nThe chapter thus ends not with a battle victory but with an ethical victory, and the ethical victory is grounded in a theological conviction: God Most High, Possessor of heaven and earth, needs no help from the king of Sodom to fulfill His covenant promise to Abram. The very title Melchizedek had proclaimed — 'Possessor of heaven and earth' — is the reason Abram can refuse heaven's goods and earth's goods from the wrong hand. If God owns it all, then no king can give Abram what God has not already promised.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Rum yad* (raised my hand, v.22) — the standard Hebrew idiom for oath-taking, corresponding to the modern 'raise your right hand.' *Chut* (thread) and *serokh naal* (sandal strap) — two of the most trivial items of everyday life, chosen to express absolute totality of refusal. *Ashar* (make rich, v.23) — to accumulate wealth; the king of Sodom cannot be the subject of this verb in Abram's story."
